def count_na(dataframe):
    """
    Count the number of NaN values in each column of a DataFrame.
    
    Args:
        dataframe (pandas.DataFrame): The DataFrame to count NaN values from.
        
    Returns:
        None (prints the column names and the number of NaN values)
    """
    for column in dataframe.columns:
        # Count the number of NaN values in the current column
        num_na = dataframe[column].isna().sum()
        
        # Print the column name and the number of NaN values
        print(f"Column '{column}' has {num_na} NaN values.")

# create visualizations based on datatype 
def draw_plots(dataframe):
    # Create a list of column names for different data types
    numeric_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['int', 'float']).columns
    object_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
    datetime_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['datetime']).columns

    # Draw box plots for numeric columns
    for column in numeric_columns:
        plt.figure()
        plt.boxplot(dataframe[column])
        plt.title(f'{column} Box Plot')

    # Draw pie charts or bar charts for object columns
    for column in object_columns:
        if dataframe[column].nunique() <= 5:
            # Draw pie chart
            plt.figure()
            value_counts = dataframe[column].value_counts()
            value_counts.plot(kind='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%')
            plt.title(f'{column} Pie Chart')
            plt.ylabel('')
            plt.legend(labels=value_counts.index, loc='best')
        else:
            # Draw bar chart
            plt.figure()
            value_counts = dataframe[column].value_counts()
            if dataframe[column].nunique() > 50:
                # Limit to top 20 and bottom 20 values
                top_bottom_counts = pd.concat([value_counts.head(20), value_counts.tail(20)])
                top_bottom_counts.plot(kind='bar')
                plt.title(f'{column} Bar Chart (Top 20 and Bottom 20)')
            else:
                value_counts.plot(kind='bar')
                plt.title(f'{column} Bar Chart')
            plt.xlabel(column)
            plt.ylabel('Count')

    # Draw line graph for datetime columns
    for column in datetime_columns:
        plt.figure()
        value_counts = dataframe[column].value_counts().sort_index()
        value_counts.plot(kind='line')
        plt.title(f'{column} Line Graph')
        plt.xlabel('Date')
        plt.ylabel('Count')

    # Display the plots
    plt.show()

# Perform logistic lasso with cross-validation
clf = LassoCV(cv=5, random_state=42, max_iter=10000, alphas=[0.1, 1, 10]).fit(X, y) #lasso would choose the best alpha by itself

# Get the selected features
selected_features = X.columns[clf.coef_ != 0]
print("Selected features:", selected_features)

# Print out the alpha score for each selected feature
for feature in selected_features:
    coef_idx = np.where(X.columns == feature)[0][0]
    coef = clf.coef_[coef_idx]
    print(f"{feature}: coef={coef}")

visualization of relationship of selected features and target variable¶

In [33]:
# Loop over input variables to create scatter plot or bar chart for each of them
for var in selected_features:
    # Retrieve float and integer variables
    if cleaned_df_filled[var].dtype == 'float64' or cleaned_df_filled[var].dtype == 'int64':
        # Generate scatter plot with feature name on horizontal axis and days on market on vertical axis
        plt.scatter(cleaned_df_filled[var], cleaned_df_filled["days_on_market"])
        # Label for x axis
        plt.xlabel(var)
        # Label for y axis
        plt.ylabel("Days on Market")
        # Show
        plt.show()
    # Retrieve all the other variables with object data type
    else:
        # Count number of unique values of each variable
        counts = cleaned_df_filled[var].value_counts()
        # Count number of 'High' for each unique variable
        high_count = cleaned_df_filled.loc[cleaned_df_filled['days_on_market'] == 'High', var].value_counts()
        # Percentage of 'High' for each value
        high_percentage = (high_count / counts) * 100
        # Retrieve top 15
        top_15 = high_percentage.nlargest(15)
        # Retrieve bottom 15
        bottom_15 = high_percentage.nsmallest(15)
        # Combine them and sort from low to high
        combined = pd.concat([top_15, bottom_15]).sort_values()
        # Filter out values with count >= 50
        filtered_combined = combined[combined.index.isin(counts[counts >= 50].index)]
        # Plot the bar chart
        filtered_combined.plot.bar()
        # Variable name for x label
        plt.xlabel(var)
        # Y label
        plt.ylabel("% High")
        # Rotate the x-axis tick labels by 90 degrees for better visibility
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        # Show
        plt.show()

# Loop over input variables to create scatter plot or bar chart for each of them
for var in selected_features:
    # Retrieve float and integer variables
    if cleaned_df_filled[var].dtype == 'float64' or cleaned_df_filled[var].dtype == 'int64':
        # Generate scatter plot with feature name on horizontal axis and days on market on vertical axis
        plt.scatter(cleaned_df_filled[var], cleaned_df_filled["days_on_market"])
        # Label for x axis
        plt.xlabel(var)
        # Label for y axis
        plt.ylabel("Days on Market")
        # Show
        plt.show()
    # Retrieve all the other variables with object data type
    else:
        # Count number of unique values of each variable
        counts = cleaned_df_filled[var].value_counts()
        # Count number of 'High' for each unique variable
        high_count = cleaned_df_filled.loc[cleaned_df_filled['days_on_market'] == 'High', var].value_counts()
        # Percentage of 'High' for each value
        high_percentage = (high_count / counts) * 100
        # Filter out values with count >= 50 and select top 15 and bottom 15
        filtered_combined = pd.concat([high_percentage[counts >= 50].nlargest(15), high_percentage[counts >= 50].nsmallest(15)])
        # Sort from low to high
        filtered_combined = filtered_combined.sort_values()
        # Plot the bar chart
        filtered_combined.plot.bar()
        # Variable name for x label
        plt.xlabel(var)
        # Y label
        plt.ylabel("% High")
        # Rotate the x-axis tick labels by 90 degrees for better visibility
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        
        # Show
        plt.show()

Data cluster¶

In [35]:
#Determine the optimal number of clusters by elbow method using metrix inertias 
inertias = [] #sum of squared distances between each data point and its closest centroid
for k in range(1, 9):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=10, n_init = 10)
    kmeans.fit(X_selected)
    inertias.append(kmeans.inertia_)
plt.plot(range(1, 9), inertias)
plt.title('Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.show()

# Define the parameter grid 
param_grid = {'n_neighbors': [2, 3, 5, 7],
              'metric': ['euclidean', 'manhattan', 'chebyshev']}

# Create an instance for the KNN model
My_KNN_grid = KNeighborsClassifier()

# Perform grid search with cross-validation
grid_search = GridSearchCV(My_KNN_grid, param_grid, scoring='roc_auc', cv=5)

# Fit the grid search object to the data
grid_search.fit(X_selected, y)

ROC Curve¶

In [83]:
#retrieve the actual output and store it as y_true 
y_true = y
In [84]:
#Predict the class probabilities for ANN
y_pred_prob_ANN = cross_val_predict(My_ANN, X_selected, y, cv=5, method='predict_proba')[:, 1]
In [85]:
#Predict the class probabilities for DT
y_pred_prob_DT = cross_val_predict(My_DT, X_selected, y, cv=5, method='predict_proba')[:, 1]
In [86]:
#Predict the class probabilities for KNN
y_pred_prob_KNN = cross_val_predict(My_KNN, X_selected, y, cv=5, method='predict_proba')[:, 1]
In [87]:
#Predict the class probabilities for BNB
y_pred_prob_BNB = cross_val_predict(My_BNB, X_selected, y, cv=5, method='predict_proba')[:, 1]
In [88]:
# Calculate false positive rate and true positive rate at different thresholds
fpr_ANN, tpr_ANN, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred_prob_ANN)
fpr_DT, tpr_DT, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred_prob_DT)
fpr_KNN, tpr_KNN, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred_prob_KNN)
fpr_BNB, tpr_BNB, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred_prob_BNB)

# Calculate the area under the ROC curve (AUC)
roc_auc_ANN = auc(fpr_ANN, tpr_ANN)
roc_auc_DT = auc(fpr_DT, tpr_DT)
roc_auc_KNN = auc(fpr_KNN, tpr_KNN)
roc_auc_BNB = auc(fpr_BNB, tpr_BNB)

# Plot the ROC curve
plt.plot(fpr_ANN, tpr_ANN, label='ANN (AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc_ANN)
plt.plot(fpr_DT, tpr_DT, label='DT (AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc_DT)
plt.plot(fpr_KNN, tpr_KNN, label='KNN (AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc_KNN)
plt.plot(fpr_BNB, tpr_BNB, label='BNB (AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc_BNB)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')  # Plot the random guess line 
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()
